Motivating example¶

Suppose we are marketing analysts and working with a client company -- a credit card company which wants to advertise its credit card offer to Amazon‘s users. The company buys a dataset from Amazon. It contains some Amazon users’ recent purchase spending amounts, age and their responses (i.e., clicking) towards online advertisements. The credit card company wants to develop a prediction model to predict whether an Amazon user would be willing to click or not on its credit card banner advertisement

The first step is to load the dataset, and see some overall picture of data using descriptive analytics. In Python, we can use pandas library to load the dataset into Jupyter notebook and check the data variables and dimension.

import pandas as pd

Logistic regression¶

In the following, we are going to develop a logistic regression model to predict whether a new advertisement will be clicked or not when we are given the values of Spending and Age.

Mathematical setting of data¶

Let's set up the mathematical notations at the beginning. We denote the dataset $\mathcal{D}$, where

$$\mathcal{D} = \{(\boldsymbol{x}_1, y_1), \cdots, (\boldsymbol{x}_N, y_N)\} = \{(\boldsymbol{x}_n, y_n)\}_{n=1}^{N}$$$$ \boldsymbol{X} = \left[ \begin{array}{ccc} x_{11} & \cdots & x_{1D} \\ \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ x_{N1} & \cdots & x_{ND} \\ \end{array} \right] = \left[ \begin{array}{c} \boldsymbol{x}_1^\top \\ \vdots\\ \boldsymbol{x}_N^\top \\ \end{array} \right] , \ \ \ \ \ \boldsymbol{y} = \left[ \begin{array}{ccc} y_{1} \\ \vdots \\ y_{N} \\ \end{array} \right]$$

In logistic regression, we employ the linear form to represent the contributions/effects of variables towards the response prediction. Specifically, each variable has a weight and the total contribution of variables is the linear combination of variables' values and their weights. Similar to multiple linear regression, we often absorb the bias term $w_0$ into the weight vector for multiple logistic regression $$ \boldsymbol{w} = \left[ \begin{array}{c} w_0\\ w_1 \\ \vdots\\ w_D \\ \end{array} \right] $$

The input matrix and vectors are adjusted as follows: $$ \boldsymbol{X} = \left[ \begin{array}{cccc} 1 & x_{11} & \cdots & x_{1D} \\ \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ 1 & x_{N1} & \cdots & x_{ND} \\ \end{array} \right] = \left[ \begin{array}{c} \boldsymbol{x}_1^\top \\ \vdots\\ \boldsymbol{x}_N^\top \\ \end{array} \right], $$ where $\boldsymbol{x}_1^\top = [1, x_{11}, \ldots, x_{1D}]$

Logistic/sigmoid function¶

We use the logistic function (also called sigmoid function) to convert the total contribution of variables/features into probability which shows how likely the event or behavior will occur. The following is the mathematical definition of logistic regression and how does it look like in terms of domain and co-domain.

For any $x \in \mathbb{R}$, the logistic/sigmoid function $f(x)$ is defined as $$f(x) = \frac{e^{x}}{1+ e^{x}},$$ therefore, $f(x) \in [0,1]$

In logistic regression, the total contribution of variables/features for the $n$th sample is defined by

$$z_n = \boldsymbol{w}^\top \boldsymbol{x}_n.$$

The probability of the sample to be clicked can be estimated by the logistic function as follows

$$p_n = \mathbb{P}(y_n=1 | \boldsymbol{x}_n) =\frac{e^{z_n}}{1+ e^{z_n}}.$$

In other words, once the weight vector $\boldsymbol{w}$ is determined, we can obtain the logistic regression for predicting future transactions.

Estimating the weights¶

There are two major ways to estimate the weights of logistic regression: maximum likelihood and cross-entropy.

Maximum likelihood¶

Since \begin{align*} p_n = & \ \mathbb{P}(y=1 | \boldsymbol{x}_n) = \frac{e^{\boldsymbol{w}^\top \boldsymbol{x}_n}}{1+ e^{\boldsymbol{w}^\top \boldsymbol{x}_n}},\\ 1- p_n = & \ \mathbb{P}(y=0 | \boldsymbol{x}_n) = \frac{1}{1+ e^{\boldsymbol{w}^\top \boldsymbol{x}_n}}. \end{align*}

The likelihood of $\boldsymbol{w}$ is given \begin{align*} \mathscr{L}(\boldsymbol{w}) & = \mathbb{P}(\boldsymbol{y} | \boldsymbol{w}, \boldsymbol{X}) \\ & = \prod_{n=1}^{N} \mathbb{P}(y_n | \boldsymbol{w}, \boldsymbol{x}_n) \\ & = \prod_{n=1}^{N} p_n^{y_n} \big(1- p_n \big)^{1-y_n}. \end{align*}

The optimal $\boldsymbol{w}^*$ can be obtained by maximizing $\mathscr{L}(\boldsymbol{w}) $. However, directly calculating $\mathscr{L}(\boldsymbol{w})$ is computationally difficult, instead, we can obtain $\boldsymbol{w}^*$ by maximizing log-likelihood $\log\{\mathscr{L}(\boldsymbol{w})\}$.

The log-likelihood of $\boldsymbol{w}$ is given

\begin{align*} \text{LL}(\boldsymbol{w}) & = \log \{ \mathscr{L}(\boldsymbol{w}) \} \\ & = \log \bigg\{ \prod_{n=1}^{N} p_n^{y_n} \big(1- p_n \big)^{1-y_n} \bigg\} \\ & = \sum_{n=1}^{N} \bigg[ y_n \log \big\{ p_n \big\} + (1 - y_n) \log \big\{ 1 - p_n \big\} \bigg] \\ & = \sum_{n=1}^{N} \bigg[ y_n \boldsymbol{w}^\top \boldsymbol{x}_n - \log \Big\{ (1 + \boldsymbol{w}^\top \boldsymbol{x}_n \Big\} \bigg] \end{align*}

Therefore, the optimal $\boldsymbol{w}^*$ can be obtained by $$ \text{max} \ \text{LL}(\boldsymbol{w}) $$

Cross-entropy¶

Cross entropy is a measure from information theory, which shows the distance between two probability distributions $p$ and $q$ over the same underlying set of events. $$ H(p,q) = - \mathbb{E}_p[\log q] = - \sum_x p(x) \log\{q(x) \}. $$

In machine learning, cross-entropy is often used as the loss function to evaluate the performance of a classification model whose output is a probability between 0 and 1. For logistic regression, the cross-entropy loss function can be defined as follows:

\begin{align*} \text{EN}(\boldsymbol{w}) & = H(\boldsymbol{y}, \boldsymbol{p}) = - \sum_{n=1}^{N} \bigg[ y_n \log \big\{ p_n \big\} + (1 - y_n) \log \big\{ 1 - p_n \big\} \bigg] \end{align*}

Therefore, the optimal $\boldsymbol{w}^*$ can be obtained by

$$ \text{min} \ \text{EN}(\boldsymbol{w}) $$

Equivalence of log-likelihood and cross-entropy as loss¶

For logistic regression, maximizing the log-likelihood is equivalent to minimizing the negative log-likelihood (NLL), and is equivalent to minimizing the cross entropy:

$$ \text{max} \ \text{LL}(\boldsymbol{w}) \Leftrightarrow \text{min} \ \text{NLL}(\boldsymbol{w}) \Leftrightarrow \text{min} \ \text{EN}(\boldsymbol{w}) $$

The difference between likelihood and cross-entropy is that the former represents a structured and principled statistical approach to modeling while the latter represents performance based training (because machine learning models aim to achieve good performance at the tasks which people are interested).

The discussion can be extended to the multiclass case by using the multinoulli likelihood and the softmax cross-entropy.

Newton's method¶

We know that we can obtain the optimal weights of logistic regression by maximizing the log-likelihood or minimizing the cross-entropy, so we just need to solve this optimization problem! There are several methods can be used. Here we study Newton's method.

Newton's method (also known as Newton-Raphson method) is an iterative algorithm to quickly find a good approximation for the root of a real-valued function $f(x)$, which are solutions to the equation $f(x)=0$. It uses the idea that a continuous and differentiable function can be approximated by a straight line tangent to it. The following is the GIF illustration on wikipedia. The function $f(x)$ is shown in blue and the tangent line is in red. We see that the next guess of root $x_{i+1}$ is a better approximation than the previous guess $x_i$ for the root $x$ of the function $f(x)$.

We can simply write Newton's method in terms of algorithm as follows

    1:   Choose initial guess of the root $x_0$
    2:   Update the guess of the root $x_{i} = x_{i-1} - \frac{f(x_{i-1})}{f^\prime(x_{i-1} )}$, where $i$ is the index starting from 1.
    3:   Update the value of function $y_{i} = f(x_{i})$.
    4:   Repeat steps 2 and 3 until $y_{i} - y_{i-1} \approx 0$.
    5:   Return the root $x_i$

In optimization, Newton's method is applied to the derivative $f^\prime(x)$ of a twice-differentiable function $f(x)$ to find the roots of the derivative, which are the solutions to equation $f^\prime(x) = 0$, also known as the stationary points of $f(x)$. These solutions may be minima, maxima, or saddle points.

In logistic regression, let's consider the log likelihood function $\text{LL}(\boldsymbol{w})$. The maxima of $\text{LL}(\boldsymbol{w})$ correspond to points where its first derivative $\nabla \text{LL}(\boldsymbol{w})=0$. Therefore, we can have the following algorithm for the estimation of $\boldsymbol{w}$.

    1:   Choose initial guess of $\boldsymbol{w}_0$
    2:   Update the guess $$\boldsymbol{w}_{i} = \boldsymbol{w}_{i-1} - \boldsymbol{H}^{-1} \nabla_{\boldsymbol{w}} \text{LL}(\boldsymbol{w}_{i-1}),$$          where $i$ is the index starting from 1, $\nabla_{\boldsymbol{w}} \text{LL}(\boldsymbol{w}_{i-1})$ is the derivative of $\text{LL}(\boldsymbol{w}_{i-1})$ with respect to $\boldsymbol{w}_{i-1}$, and $\boldsymbol{H}^{-1}$ is the inverse of Hessian matrix.
    3:   Update the value of function $y_{i} = \text{LL}(\boldsymbol{w}_{i})$.
    4:   Repeat steps 2 and 3 until $y_{i} - y_{i-1} \approx 0$.
    5:   Return the root $\boldsymbol{w}_{i}$
"Newton’s method typically enjoys faster convergence than (batch) gradient descent, and requires many fewer iterations to get very close to the minimum. One iteration of Newton’s can, however, be more expensive than one iteration of gradient descent, since it requires finding and inverting an $n$-by-$n$ Hessian; but so long as n is not too large, it is usually much faster overall. When Newton’s method is applied to maximize the logistic regression log likelihood function $\text{LL}(\boldsymbol{w})$, the resulting method is also called Fisher scoring."
-- Andrew Ng, Stanford CS229 Machine Learning Notes

sklearn to solve the optimization for logistic regression¶

In sklearn, the class sklearn.linear_model.LogisticRegression provides the following solvers

{‘newton-cg’, ‘lbfgs’, ‘liblinear’, ‘sag’, ‘saga’}, default=’lbfgs’

Algorithm to use in the optimization problem.

For small datasets, ‘liblinear’ is a good choice, whereas ‘sag’ and ‘saga’ are faster for large ones.

For multiclass problems, only ‘newton-cg’, ‘sag’, ‘saga’ and ‘lbfgs’ handle multinomial loss; ‘liblinear’ is limited to one-versus-rest schemes.

‘newton-cg’, ‘lbfgs’, ‘sag’ and ‘saga’ handle L2 or no penalty

‘liblinear’ and ‘saga’ also handle L1 penalty

‘saga’ also supports ‘elasticnet’ penalty

‘liblinear’ does not support setting penalty='none'

https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.linear_model.LogisticRegression.html

Train logistic regression in sklearn¶

We want to use sklearn library to train/develop a logistic regression model. The first step is to convert the loaded data into ndarray of numpy

x = df.iloc[:, :-1].to_numpy()
y = df.iloc[:, -1].to_numpy()

Let's then randomly split the dataset into 70% training and 30% test

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=0)

The training and test sets of data after splitting can be visualised as follows:

Now let's train/develop a logistic regression model using the training set

from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
clf = LogisticRegression(random_state=0, solver="liblinear")
clf.fit(x_train, y_train)

Note that the solver in optimization can be replaced with other candidates, such as ‘newton-cg’, ‘lbfgs’, ‘liblinear’, ‘sag’, ‘saga’

Let's take a look at what does the trained logistic regression look like.

Confusion matrix¶

Based on our threshold/decision boundary, we can evaluate how many positive and negative samples are correctly predicted/classified by the trained logistic regression. Remember, so far we are looking at the training data.

The following is the so-called confusion matrix, where

  • True positive (TP) represents the model predicts positive and its prediction is correct. Here in our example positive means click.
  • True negative (TN) represents the model predicts negative and its prediction is correct. Here in our example negative means no click.
  • False positive (FP) represents the model predicts positive but its prediction is incorrect.
  • False negative (FN) represents the model predicts negative and its prediction is incorrect.

We can quickly calculate the TP, TN, FP, FN:

tp = df_result_training[(df_result_training["Label_Pred"]==1) & (df_result_training["Label_GT"]==1)].shape[0]
tn = df_result_training[(df_result_training["Label_Pred"]==0) & (df_result_training["Label_GT"]==0)].shape[0]
fp = df_result_training[(df_result_training["Label_Pred"]==1) & (df_result_training["Label_GT"]==0)].shape[0]
fn = df_result_training[(df_result_training["Label_Pred"]==0) & (df_result_training["Label_GT"]==1)].shape[0]

Alternatively, we can use the function from sklearn to calculate confusion matrix and use seaborn to visualize it

from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

cf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_train, y_pred_train)

group_names = ["TN", "FP", "FN", "TP"]
group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}".format(value) for value in cf_matrix.flatten()]
group_percentages = [
    "{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in cf_matrix.flatten() / np.sum(cf_matrix)]
labels = [f"{v1}\n{v2}\n{v3}" for v1, v2, v3 in zip(group_names, group_counts, group_percentages)]
labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2, 2)

fig=plt.figure()
sns.heatmap(cf_matrix, annot=labels, fmt="", cmap="Blues")
plt.show()

Let's see how TP, TN, FP, FN are obtained based on our threshold/decision boundary.

Accuracy, recall, precision and F1 score¶

Based on confusion matrix, we can define the following evaluation metrics:

  • Accuracy is the most intuitive performance measure and it is simply a ratio of correctly predicted observation to the total observations.
\begin{align*} \text{Accuracy} & \ = \frac{\text{TP} + \text{TN}}{\text{FP} + \text{FN} + \text{TP} + \text{TN}} \\ \text{Error Rate} & \ = \frac{\text{FP} + \text{FN}}{\text{FP} + \text{FN} + \text{TP} + \text{TN}} = 1 - \text{Accuracy} \\ \end{align*}
  • Precision is the ratio of correctly predicted positive observations to the total predicted positive observations. The question that this metric answer is of all advertisements that are predicted to be clicked, how many actually are clicked?
\begin{align*} \text{Precision} & \ = \frac{\text{TP}}{\text{TP} + \text{FP}} \end{align*}
  • Recall or true positive rate (TPR) is the ratio of correctly predicted positive observations to the all observations in actual class. The question recall answers is that that of all the advertisements that are truly clicked, how many did we predict?
\begin{align*} \text{True Positive Rate (TPR)} & \ = \text{Recall} = \frac{\text{TP}}{\text{TP} + \text{FN}}\\ \text{False Positive Rate (FPR)} & \ = \frac{\text{FP}}{\text{FP} + \text{TN}} \end{align*}
  • F1 score is the weighted average of precision and recall. Therefore, this score takes both false positives and false negatives into account. Intuitively it is not as easy to understand as accuracy, but F1 is usually more useful than accuracy, especially if you have an uneven class distribution. Accuracy works best if false positives and false negatives have similar cost. If the cost of false positives and false negatives are very different, it’s better to look at both Precision and Recall.
\begin{align*} \text{F1 Score} & \ = \frac{2 \times \text{Recall} \times \text{Precision}}{\text{Recall} + \text{Precision}} \end{align*}

In Python, we can use sklearn to calculate the above evaluation metrics

from sklearn.metrics import classification_report
print(classification_report(y_train, y_pred_train))

              precision    recall  f1-score   support

           0       0.92      0.32      0.48        37
           1       0.80      0.99      0.89       103

weighted avg       0.83      0.81      0.78       140

Receiver operator characteristic (ROC) curve¶

The ROC curve illustrates the true positive rate (TPR) against false positive rate (FPR) of our model. We are hoping the ROC curve will hug the upper left corner of our graph. A classifier with 50-50 accuracy is deemed 'worthless'; this is no better then random guessing, as in the case of a coin flip.

The area under the ROC curve (simply AUC) gives a numerical measure between 0 and 1 for model's classification performance

The following toy example show when the trained model can perfectly predict positive and negative samples, the AUC is equal 1.

The following toy example show when the trained model's performance is poor, almost similar to random guess like we flip a fair coin, so its AUC is equal 0.5.

We can use sklearn library to calculate ROC and AUC, and then plot ROC diagram for the logistic regression model.

from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, auc

fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_train, y_prob_train)
roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)

plt.figure(figsize=[7, 6])
plt.plot(
    fpr, tpr, label="Logistic regression (AUC={:0.2f})".format(roc_auc), linewidth=2
)
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color="green", linestyle="--", label="Random (AUC=0.50)")
plt.xlabel("FPR", fontsize=13)
plt.ylabel("TPR", fontsize=13)
plt.legend(loc="lower right", fontsize=13)
plt.show()
So far we have evaluated the logistic regression model with the training data. Same evaluation operations can be applied to the test data set. I will leave this as an exercise for workshop practice.
